"Bernardo J., Spotila J.R.","Physiological constraints on organismal response to global warming: Mechanistic insights from clinally varying populations and implications for assessing endangerment",2006,"Biology Letters","2","1",,"135","139",,,10.1098/rsbl.2005.0417,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33644926393&partnerID=40&md5=a4c06ff145cd322a571a22a1bb71ff11","Department of Biology, College of Charleston, 66 George Street, Charleston, SC 29424, United States; Southern Appalachian Biodiversity Institute, Roan Mountain, TN 37687-3544, United States; Center for Biodiversity and Conservation, Department of Bioscience and Biotechnology, Drexel University, 3141 Chestnut Street, Philadelphia, PA 19104, United States","Bernardo, J., Department of Biology, College of Charleston, 66 George Street, Charleston, SC 29424, United States, Southern Appalachian Biodiversity Institute, Roan Mountain, TN 37687-3544, United States; Spotila, J.R., Center for Biodiversity and Conservation, Department of Bioscience and Biotechnology, Drexel University, 3141 Chestnut Street, Philadelphia, PA 19104, United States","Recent syntheses indicate that global warming affects diverse biological processes, but also highlight the potential for some species to adapt behaviourally or evolutionarily to rapid climate change. Far less attention has addressed the alternative, that organisms lacking this ability may face extinction, a fate projected to befall one-quarter of global biodiversity. This conclusion is controversial, in part because there exist few mechanistic studies that show how climate change could precipitate extinction. We provide a concrete, mechanistic example of warming as a stressor of organisms that are closely adapted to cool climates from a comparative analysis of organismal tolerance among clinally varying populations along a natural thermal gradient. We found that two montane salamanders exhibit significant metabolic depression at temperatures within the natural thermal range experienced by low and middle elevation populations. Moreover, the magnitude of depression was inversely related to native elevation, suggesting that low elevation populations are already living near the limit of their physiological tolerances. If this finding generally applies to other montane specialists, the prognosis for biodiversity loss in typically diverse montane systems is sobering. We propose that indices of warming-induced stress tolerance may provide a critical new tool for quantitative assessments of endangerment due to anthropogenic climate change across diverse species. © 2005 The Royal Society.","Climate change; Conservation assessment; Environmental stress; Life history; Metabolic depression; Salamander","climate change; environmental stress; life history; physiological response; animal experiment; article; climate change; cold climate; controlled study; endangered species; greenhouse effect; heat tolerance; metabolic inhibition; nonhuman; organismal interaction; priority journal; quantitative analysis; salamander; stress; Animals; Extinction, Biological; Greenhouse Effect; Population; Temperature; Urodela; Amphiuma means; Animalia; Caudata",,,,,,"Addo-Bediako, A., Chown, S.L., Gaston, K.J., Thermal tolerance, climatic variability and latitude (2000) Proc. R. Soc. B, 267, pp. 739-745. , doi:10.1098/rspb.2000.1065; Bernardo, J., Experimental analysis of allocation in two divergent, natural salamander populations (1994) Am. Nat., 143, pp. 14-38. , doi:10.1086/285594; Bernardo, J., The logic, value and necessity of grounding experiments in quantitative field data: An essential link in the inferential chain back to nature (1998) Experimental Ecology: Issues and Perspectives, pp. 370-393. , (ed. W. J. Resetarits & J. Bernardo). New York: Oxford University Press; Bernardo, J., Natural history notes: Desmognathus carolinenesis and Plethodon wellen; Desmognathus monticola and Desmognathus wrighti; Gyrinophilus porphyriticus and Desmognathus ocoee (Ocoee salamander). Intraguild predation (2002) Herpetol. Rev., 33, p. 121; Bernardo, J., Agosta, S., Determinants of clinal variation in life history of dusky salamanders (Desmognathus ocoee): Prey abundance and ecological limits on foraging time restrict opportunities for larval growth (2003) J. Zool. Lond., 259, pp. 411-421; Bernardo, J., Reagan-Wallin, N.L., Plethodontid salamanders do not conform to ""general rules"" for ectotherm life histories: Insights from allocation models about why simple models do not make accurate predictions (2002) Oikos, 97, pp. 398-414. , doi:10.1034/j.1600-0706.2002.970310.x; Bradshaw, W.E., Holzapfel, C.M., Genetic shift in photoperiodic response correlated with global warming (2001) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci., 98, pp. 14509-14511. , doi:10.1073/pnas.241391498; Davis, M.B., Shaw, R.G., Range shifts and adaptive responses to quaternary climate change (2001) Science, 292, pp. 673-679. , doi:10.1126/science.292.5517.673; Etheridge, K., The energetics of estivating sirenid salamanders (Siren lacertina and Pseudobranchus striatus) (1990) Herpetologica, 46, pp. 407-414; Feder, M.E., Bennett, A.F., Huey, R.B., Evolutionary physiology (2000) Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst., 31, pp. 315-341. , doi:10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.31.1.315; Garland, T., Adolph, S.C., Physiological differentiation of vertebrate populations (1991) Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst., 22, pp. 193-228. , doi:10.1146/annurev.es.22.110191.001205; Gaston, K.J., Chown, S.L., Elevation and climatic tolerance: A test using dung beetles (1999) Oikos, 86, pp. 584-590; (2002) Climate Change and Biodiversity, , Gitay, H., Suarez, A., Dokken, D. J. & Watson, R. T. (eds). Inter-governmental Panel on Climate Change, Technical Paper V. Geneva, Switzerland; Guppy, M., Withers, P., Metabolic depression in animals: Physiological perspectives and biochemical generalizations (1999) Biol. Rev., 74, pp. 1-40. , doi:10.1017/S0006323198005258; Hairston, N.G., Species packing in Desmognathus salamanders: Experimental demonstration of predation and competition (1986) Am. Nat., 127, pp. 266-291. , doi:10.1086/284485; Hoffmann, A.A., Hallas, R., Deans, J., Schiffer, M., Low potential for climate stress adaptation in a rainforest Drosophila species (2003) Science, 301, pp. 100-102. , doi:10.1126/science.1084296; (2001) The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. 2001 Categories & Criteria (Version 3.1), , http://www.iucnredlist.org/info/categories_criteria2001.html; (2002) Mountain Biodiversity: A Global Assessment, , Körner, C. & Spehn, E. M. (eds). New York: CRC Press; Lawton, R.O., Nair, U.S., Pielke, R.A., Welch, R.M., Climatic impact of tropical lowland deforestation on nearby montane cloud forests (2001) Science, 294, pp. 584-587; Parmesan, C., Climate and species range (1996) Nature, 382, pp. 765-766. , doi:10.1038/382765a0; Parmesan, C., Yohe, G., A globally coherent fingerprint of climate change impacts across natural systems (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 37-42. , doi:10.1038/nature01286; Parmesan, C., Poleward shift of butterfly species' ranges associated with regional warming (1999) Nature, 399, pp. 579-583. , doi:10.1038/21181; Peterson, A.T., Ortega-Huerta, M.A., Bartley, J., Sanchez-Cordero, V., Soberon, J., Buddemeier, R.H., Stockwell, D.R.B., Future projections for Mexican faunas under global climate change scenarios (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 626-629. , doi:10.1038/416626a; Pounds, J.A., Fogden, M.P.L., Campbell, J.H., Biological response to climate change on a tropical mountain (1999) Nature, 398, pp. 611-615. , doi:10.1038/19297; Root, T.L., Price, J.T., Hall, K.R., Schneider, S.H., Rosenzweig, C., Pounds, J.A., Fingerprints of global warming on wild animals and plants (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 57-60. , doi:10.1038/nature01333; Still, C.J., Foster, P.N., Schneider, S.H., Simulating the effects of climate change on tropical montane cloud forests (1999) Nature, 398, pp. 608-610. , doi:10.1038/19293; Thomas, C.D., Extinction risk from climate change (2004) Nature, 427, pp. 145-14